==Abstract==

This IIP proposes increasing the maximum OP_RETURN data size from 83 bytes to 4096 bytes to accommodate post-quantum payment code notification transactions.

==Motivation==

BIP47 reusable payment codes enable privacy-preserving recurring payments by deriving unique addresses for each transaction between parties. The notification transaction carries the sender's payment code to the recipient.

With INTcoin's post-quantum cryptography:
* ML-DSA-87 public keys are 2592 bytes
* Payment code notifications require transmitting key material
* The current 83-byte OP_RETURN limit is insufficient

Without this change, payment codes cannot be implemented on INTcoin.

==Specification==

===Consensus Rule Change===

The maximum data pushable in an OP_RETURN output is increased from 83 bytes to 4096 bytes.

===Activation===

This change activates via BIP9-style version bits signaling:

{| class="wikitable"
|-
! Parameter !! Value
|-
| Bit || 4
|-
| Name || extended_opreturn
|-
| Start Time || Genesis (1773014400)
|-
| Timeout || No timeout
|-
| Threshold || 90% (mainnet), 75% (testnet)
|-
| Min Activation Height || 1000 (mainnet), 100 (testnet)
|}

===Transaction Validation===

After activation:
* OP_RETURN outputs with data up to 4096 bytes are standard
* OP_RETURN outputs remain provably unspendable
* Multiple OP_RETURN outputs per transaction are NOT permitted
* Total transaction size limits still apply

===Standardness Rules===

Pre-activation:
* OP_RETURN data > 83 bytes is non-standard (not relayed)

Post-activation:
* OP_RETURN data up to 4096 bytes is standard
* OP_RETURN data > 4096 bytes remains non-standard

==Rationale==

===Why 4KB?===

4096 bytes provides sufficient space for:
* Full payment code with ML-DSA-87 keys (~2700 bytes)
* Encrypted metadata
* Future extensibility

It is small enough to prevent blockchain bloat abuse while enabling legitimate use cases.

===Why Version Bits?===

Version bits activation ensures:
* Network-wide coordination
* Miners signal readiness
* Safe rollout with fallback

===Why Not Multiple OP_RETURNs?===

Keeping the single OP_RETURN rule:
* Simplifies indexing
* Prevents circumventing size limits
* Maintains backward compatibility for parsers

==Backwards Compatibility==

* Pre-activation: Extended OP_RETURN transactions are non-standard but valid
* Post-activation: All nodes must accept extended OP_RETURN
* Old wallet software may not recognize extended OP_RETURN data

